    state: '<STATE>',
});
```
{% /multicode %}

The user is shown exactly these scopes on your consent screen, where they [approve or withhold each one](/docs/partners/oauth-server/authorization#consent). Whatever they grant is what the issued access token carries in its `scope` claim, and the token response reports the granted set in its `scope` field, so a client can tell when it received less than it asked for. Request only what the integration needs; smaller requests are easier to approve.

# Rich authorization requests {% #rich-authorization-requests %}

A scope is a flat string, which works well for broad capabilities like `read:tasks` but cannot express structured constraints like "read tasks, in these two projects only". For that, the OAuth server supports rich authorization requests (RAR, [RFC 9396](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9396)): the client sends an `authorization_details` parameter, a JSON array of objects that each describe one grant of access in your product's own vocabulary.

Scopes and authorization details are not exclusive. Use scopes for broad capabilities, and add authorization details when an integration needs caveats a flat string cannot carry.

## Define accepted types {% #define-authorization-details-types %}

Think of an `authorization_details` entry as a small form the client fills in to ask for access. The `type` is the name printed at the top of the form. When your API sees `"type": "tasks"`, it knows it is reading the "access to tasks" form, so it knows what the other fields on it mean: which actions, which projects.

For the task example, the two mechanisms cover the same resource at different granularities:

- The `read:tasks` **scope** grants blanket read access to every task.
- A `tasks` **entry** describes task access with constraints attached, such as which actions and which projects.

An integration that needs everything requests the scope. One that should only touch part of the data requests a `tasks` entry instead.

The OAuth server only accepts types you have allowed on the project. Define them with the `authorizationDetailsTypes` parameter:

{% multicode %}
```server-nodejs
import { Client, Project } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1') // Your API Endpoint
    .setProject('<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>') // Your project ID
    .setKey('<YOUR_API_KEY>'); // Your secret API key

const project = new Project(client);

const result = await project.updateOAuth2Server({
    enabled: true,
    authorizationUrl: 'https://your-product.com/oauth/consent',
    scopes: ['read:tasks', 'write:tasks'],
    authorizationDetailsTypes: ['tasks'],
});
```
```server-php
<?php

use Appwrite\Client;
use Appwrite\Services\Project;

$client = (new Client())
    ->setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1') // Your API Endpoint
    ->setProject('<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>') // Your project ID
    ->setKey('<YOUR_API_KEY>'); // Your secret API key

$project = new Project($client);

$result = $project->updateOAuth2Server(
    enabled: true,
    authorizationUrl: 'https://your-product.com/oauth/consent',
    scopes: ['read:tasks', 'write:tasks'],
    authorizationDetailsTypes: ['tasks']
);
```
