```server-go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "github.com/appwrite/sdk-for-go/client"
    "github.com/appwrite/sdk-for-go/project"
)

func main() {
    c := client.New(
        client.WithEndpoint("https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1"),
        client.WithProject("<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>"),
        client.WithKey("<YOUR_API_KEY>"),
    )

    service := project.New(c)

    response, err := service.UpdateOAuth2Server(
        true,
        "https://your-product.com/oauth/consent",
        project.WithUpdateOAuth2ServerScopes([]string{"read:tasks", "write:tasks"}),
        project.WithUpdateOAuth2ServerAuthorizationDetailsTypes([]string{"tasks"}),
    )
    if err != nil {
        panic(err)
    }

    fmt.Println(response)
}
```
```server-rust
use appwrite::client::Client;
use appwrite::services::project::Project;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let client = Client::new()
        .set_endpoint("https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1") // Your API Endpoint
        .set_project("<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>") // Your project ID
        .set_key("<YOUR_API_KEY>"); // Your secret API key

    let project = Project::new(&client);

    let result = project
        .update_o_auth2_server(
            true,
            "https://your-product.com/oauth/consent",
            Some(vec!["read:tasks".into(), "write:tasks".into()]),
            Some(vec!["tasks".into()]), // authorization details types
            None,
            None,
            None,
            None,
            None,
            None,
            None,
            None,
            None,
        )
        .await?;

    let _ = result;

    Ok(())
}
```
{% /multicode %}

{% info title="The call replaces the whole configuration" %}
`updateOAuth2Server` sets the full OAuth2 server configuration in one call. Include your existing scopes and settings when adding types, or they reset to their defaults.
{% /info %}

Like scopes, a project can define up to 100 types, each up to 128 characters. The accepted types are published in the [discovery document](/docs/partners/oauth-server/quick-start#discovery) under `authorization_details_types_supported`, so integrators can see them without asking you.

## Request authorization details {% #request-authorization-details %}

A client sends its entries, JSON-encoded, as the `authorization_details` parameter on the same [authorize request](/docs/partners/oauth-server/authorization#authorize) that carries `scope`:

```client-web
import { Client, Oauth2 } from 'appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://<REGION>.cloud.appwrite.io/v1') // Your API Endpoint
    .setProject('<YOUR_PROJECT_ID>'); // Your project ID

const oauth2 = new Oauth2(client);

const details = [
    {
        type: 'tasks',
        actions: ['read'],
        projects: ['launch'],
    },
];

const result = await oauth2.authorize({
    clientId: '<CLIENT_ID>',
    redirectUri: 'https://example.com/oauth/callback',
    responseType: 'code',
    scope: 'openid',
    authorizationDetails: JSON.stringify(details),
});
```

The server validates every entry before creating the grant:

- `type` is required and must be one of the types you defined. An unknown type fails the request with `invalid_authorization_details`.
- `actions`, when present, must be an array of non-empty strings.
- Every other field, like `projects` above, is yours to design. The server carries them through untouched.

## Consent and enforcement {% #authorization-details-consent %}

Authorization details ride through the flow the same way scopes do:

1. The requested details are stored on the grant, where your consent screen reads them to show the user exactly what is being asked.
2. When approving, the consent screen can pass a narrowed `authorization_details` back, the same way [consent](/docs/partners/oauth-server/authorization#consent) can grant a subset of the requested scopes. The user might approve `"actions": ["read"]` after the client asked for read and write.
3. The granted details are returned in the token response and stamped onto the access token as the `authorization_details` claim.

Enforcement works exactly like scopes. Your API reads the `authorization_details` claim from the verified access token and applies the constraints it describes. The OAuth server only carries the details; your product gives them meaning.

That includes deciding how the two mechanisms combine when a token carries both:

- If the token holds a `tasks` entry, apply its constraints: only the listed actions, only the listed projects.
- If it holds only the blanket scope, allow the whole resource.
